text: I know it’s hipster cool to drag on Stranger Things for being nostalgia porn but fuck that, it’s genuinely really good.
It’s very good. I have no nostalgia for the 80s.
I just tried it last night, I couldn’t get into it :white_frowning_face: for me it crosses the line from homage to plagiarism

If you’re gonna homage something you need to make it work. It Follows works on its own even without the 80’s horror trapping, and I think Stranger Things does too even though it’s the most obvious love letter to Stephen King ever. Plus making Steve my favorite character is brilliant
Really? Steve?
What is it plagiarizing? King? I was never a king fan so I guess I don’t see it.
I enjoy it far more than any of King’s works.
The title font is a king cover basically
Well...it’s an 80 horror view. King just had so many I think you’re attributing it to him. That font/style wasn’t exclusively King’s.
Lots of Firestarter elements in Eleven, It influences in the group of kids
I missed the scene where Eleven has sex with the others to calm them down. :smiling_imp:
Lol
These millenials wouldn’t understand how it was back then, what with the sewer gangbangs and no avocado toast
We started watching Carrie with the kids around Halloween and both quickly realized we’d only ever seen it on TV and had to quickly turn it off during the opening shower pan.
Not sure I’ve seen the non tv version either
There’s an almost 5 minutes of nude teenage girls in the locker room cavorting.
Full nude.
Also a lot of lingering slow pans up and down Sissy Spacek’s young nude body in the shower.
I can’t recall how he was in the movie but travoltas character was pretty rapey in the book
We stopped pretty quickly so I don’t know how he developed. He was pretty stupid and his girlfriend was the prototypical crazy rich bitch.

I never liked King’s characters. Most wound up caricatures. Carrie’s Mom is the religious nutjob, Travolta’s girlfriend is evil crazy for no reason, etc. He just needs them to be monosyllable story elements to drive his stories.
It’s not his strength for sure

To the plagiarism question: The gorgon uses humans as incubators like Alien, and in fact looks like it’s from Alien. The psychic nosebleeds are from Firestarter, the psychic repressed girl from Carrie, the sensory deprivation chamber from Scanners. The lost kid talking to his mom through the walls is from Poltergeist, the scientist uniforms from ET. In season 2 they lift the concept of gremlins that shouldn’t be fed too much and are allergic to light, and later steal a scene from Arachnophobia when discovering the epicenter of the town’s problems and circling them on a map. To me the series doesn’t add enough extra oomph to those concepts to be a real homage, they just feel borrowed

I think those are fair points, but I'd argue it gets way with it due to pretty excellent characterization, like Steve starting as who should be the sterotypical bad guy douche and winding up a genuine hero

It has its moments. Then it has bad ones. I just saw episode 3 of the second season last night and for a reason I cannot fully understand, a perfectly normal conversation in a car on the way to school has the ultra-creepy music beneath it. It was jarring and everyone in the room started laughing at how silly it was. Some guy tells a kid he used to be scared of clowns but he faced his fears, and this gets the same creepy music as when the kid is literally visited by monsters
Interesting. I didn’t find that scene jarring.

That was intentional to remove the normalcy from the scene. Whether to add foreboding or preparation for a future reveal we’ll know soon enough but it didn’t jar me out of the moment or feel incongruous.

It was preparation for the end of that episode when will takes the advice, but it could have been a normal scene. If the scary parts are supposed to feel scary, they need to be aesthetically separated from un-scary scenes
I can't say I noticed they weren't
It kinda felt to me like a realty tv show using dramatic music after people have conversation to try and amp up drama where there isn’t any
Reality*
Not remotely the impression I got, but to each his own
I give the directors more credit than to be that obvious. That isn’t a common technique in their repertoire so I assume it adds a layer to a later point in the story.
If it don’t, don’t say I didn’t warn ya :stuck_out_tongue_winking_eye:
I won’t.
That specific scene foreshadows a massive plot point
Yuuuge plot point. We have the biggest and best plot points in the history of plots. It's incredible how yuuuge our plots are...
Just incredible.

Obviously late to the party, but I’ve loved Stranger Things. I’m more than a bit of a Stephen King homer, and the whole series reminds me of a variety of King books, most notably It.
